tics and place; narratives of state violence; activists' experimental lifestyles; and the uneven development of democratic politics on and off the street. Lee illuminates how the interaction between official history, collective memory, and performance came to define youth citizenship and resistance in Indonesia's transition to the post-Suharto present.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aCollege studentsxPolitical activityzIndonesia. 0aNationalismzIndonesia. 0aStudent movementszIndonesia. 4aAAS Book Award Winners. 4aAsian Studies Association book awards. 4aHarry J. Benda Book Prize Winner. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374091zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374091423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374091.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles